module top(...);

input clk;
input sel;
input [3:0] ra;
input [3:0] wa;
input wd;
output [3:0] rd;

reg [3:0] mem[0:15];

integer i;
initial begin
        for (i = 0; i < 16; i = i + 1)
                mem[i] <= i;
end

assign rd = mem[ra];

always @(posedge clk) begin
        mem[wa] <= {4{sel ? wd : mem[wa][0]}};
end

endmodule
```

When this module is processed with `proc; clean; memory_share`, the `memory_share` read-to-write feedback detection gets overeager and removes (turns to X) the second input to the shared mux, even though it's only a feedback path for bit 0, causing wrong values to be written to bits 1-3 (the `mem[wa]` read port is unused and will be deleted by subsequent `clean`).

